All thresholds are comfortably clear: cognitive-complexity limit 10 (highest function ~3-4), max-depth 3 (max nesting is 2 in the double loop), max-lines-per-function 30 (largest is ~12), max-params 4 (max is 2).

The mandate is to attempt at least one refactoring. The strongest candidate is `isAliveNextGeneration`. Note rule `sonarjs/prefer-single-boolean-return` is active — the current code is two returns but does not trip it because they aren't both boolean-literal returns over the same `if`. Let me evaluate the one available structural change: collapsing the body into a single boolean expression.

Current:
```ts
if (liveNeighbors === BIRTH_NEIGHBORS) return true;
return liveNeighbors === SURVIVAL_NEIGHBORS && isCurrentlyAlive;
```

Candidate (single expression, removes the `if` branch):
```ts
return (
  liveNeighbors === BIRTH_NEIGHBORS ||
  (liveNeighbors === SURVIVAL_NEIGHBORS && isCurrentlyAlive)
);
```

This expresses the Conway rule as one boolean — "born with 3, OR survives with 2 while alive." McCabe stays at 3 (the `||` adds a path the removed `if` had), but it removes the early-return control-flow split, lowering cognitive load and APP mass (removes one conditional-block structure, the `if` statement at mass 4, replacing with a cheaper `||` operator). It also reads as the canonical statement of the rule. Let me apply and re-measure.

